THE WINTER ROAD
A Chronicle of the Skyrim Wardens

PART I: THE ABANDONED CAMP
The Letter
Dawn came grey and reluctant over the ruins of Korvanjund. The Stormcloaks were gone ΓÇö marched north before first light, their tracks already filling with fresh snow. The siege camp was a skeleton of empty tents and abandoned firepits, the wind singing through canvas that nobody had bothered to take down.
Bjorn was checking harness straps when the rider came.
He was young, Imperial, wearing the red and gold of the Legion. His horse was lathered and blowing hard, and the boy's eyes darted constantly to the tree line as if he expected blue-and-grey soldiers to materialize from the pines at any moment. He dismounted fast, scanned the group until his eyes found Davinia, and closed the distance at a half-jog.
"Lady Caelus? I have a letter from General Caelinus. He said it was urgent."
He pressed a sealed scroll into her hands ΓÇö the Imperial Dragon crest stamped in red wax ΓÇö then mounted his horse and rode south without waiting for a response. He didn't look back.
Davinia broke the seal. The others watched her face as she read, and what they saw there was not surprise but recognition. The expression of someone who had been expecting a blow and had just felt it land.
The letter was her father's voice committed to parchment ΓÇö loving, controlling, and absolute. He had arrived in Solitude. He had seen the reports from the Pale, the whispers about the Jagged Crown, a group matching her description leaving Korvanjund with Galmar Stone-Fist. He had suppressed those reports before they reached General Tullius's desk. He would not do so again.
The time for playing adventurer is over. Present yourself at Castle Dour immediately. Come home.
Three fathers now. Valerius wanted the Crown brought to him. Galmar trusted her to deliver it to Ulfric. And her actual father wanted her in a gilded office in Solitude, appointed as Imperial Liaison to the Jarls ΓÇö a position of safety, influence, and a cage with very fine bars.
Davinia folded the letter and tucked it inside her armor, next to the blood-letter from Valerius, next to the weight of Galmar's house seal. Three competing claims on her loyalty, pressed against her chest like a hand squeezing her heart.
The Crown of the Pale Lady hummed. Quiet. Satisfied. Conflict was architecture, and Ismara approved of complex structures.
The Remnant
Movement at the tree line.
Something stumbled out of the forest ΓÇö waterlogged, grey, dragging one foot through the snow. The smell arrived first: wet rot, river mud, and something chemical underneath that made Saijah cover her nose.
It was a ghoul. Alfonso's ghoul. One of the sixteen that had been destroyed in the collapsing tomb.
This one looked like it had drowned and kept walking. Its flesh was bloated grey-green, covered in dead leaves and frozen mud. Its clothing hung in tatters. Its eyes were milky white, but when its head turned toward the cart, there was recognition in them. It stopped at the edge of the clearing and stood there, waiting. It had been walking for days, following something only it could sense.
A Stormcloak straggler ΓÇö one of the lookouts who hadn't left with the column ΓÇö shouted in alarm, reaching for his weapon.
Alfonso raised his hand. Not at the soldier. At the ghoul.
He studied it for a moment with the clinical appraisal of a craftsman examining a returned tool. Then he cast. The fireball was precise, almost surgical ΓÇö it struck the ghoul dead center and blew it apart into four distinct pieces that tumbled across the snow, trailing smoke.
"They'll reform," Alfonso said to no one in particular, watching the pieces twitch. "Four of them now, instead of one. Same capabilities. Better coverage."
The Stormcloak straggler stared at the smoking chunks of flesh, then at Alfonso, then decided he urgently needed to be somewhere else. He gathered his gear and left at a pace that was almost but not quite running.
Ylva, who had been sitting by the dead fire sharpening her axe, looked up from the ghoul fragments to study the rest of the group. Her gaze landed on Davinia ΓÇö standing apart, reading the letter, radiating icy tension like a wounded animal trying not to show weakness.
That looked interesting.
Ylva stood, stretched, and walked toward the Imperial woman, leaving Alfonso to deal with his dead toys.
The Brass Tacks
When the immediate chaos settled, Bjorn called them over. He spread a worn map of Skyrim across a flat crate and weighed down the corners with stones, his weathered face serious in a way that made everyone pay attention.
"Alright. Let's talk brass tacks."
He pointed to three locations with a piece of charcoal: Korvanjund, Winterhold, Riften.
"Winterhold is four days north if we take it easy. Two days if we push hard ΓÇö sleep in shifts, eat on the cart, don't stop unless the wheels fall off. Riften is a week south from Winterhold at a comfortable pace. Maybe five days if we push."
He tapped the map.
"That courier said Hemming's been sick for three days already. Maven's healers are buying time, but not much. Figure we've got... what, a week? Maybe ten days before the rot takes him or spreads to the whole city?"
He looked at each of them.
"If we dawdle ΓÇö stop at every village, take long rests, chat with every merchant ΓÇö we'll arrive to a funeral. Maybe worse. Maybe we arrive to Riften locked down with plague spreading through the streets."
He folded the map.
"If we push ΓÇö sleep in shifts, eat on the move, skip the sightseeing ΓÇö we might make it. But we'll be tired, hungry, and running on fumes when we get there."
He looked up.
"Your call. But choose now, and stick to it. I can't push Mable into the ground. If you want speed, we do it smart. If you want thoroughness, we accept we might be too late."
They chose speed.
Bjorn climbed onto the driver's bench and took up the reins. The cart creaked as he settled his weight.
"Mount up. We leave now."
Behind them, the entrance to Korvanjund was a mountain of rubble ΓÇö sealed forever. The Stormcloak camp stood empty, tracks in the snow leading north. Galmar and his men were already gone.
The wind howled through the Pale. The road stretched ahead, white and frozen and unforgiving.
They began moving north.

PART II: THE FROZEN ROAD
The Locked Hands
The first day of travel, mid-morning. Kyboh was riding up front on the driver's bench with Bjorn. The others were in the back under the canvas ΓÇö resting, talking, or in Varon's case, walking silently alongside the cart like a shadow that preferred the ground.
The frozen road was rough, and the cart lurched over a patch of ice. A leather strap on the harness snapped with a sound like a whip crack. The cart jerked to a stop. Mable snorted in protest.
Bjorn cursed under his breath and climbed down stiffly, his breath misting in the frozen air. He moved to inspect the harness, flexing his fingers against the cold.
"I need to pull this strap tight and tie it off. Two-person job. Someone hold the leather while I knot it."
Kyboh jumped down and grabbed the broken strap. His strength made the work trivial ΓÇö he hauled the leather taut with one hand while Bjorn worked the knot.
Then his fingers locked.
Not metaphorically. Literally. The grey calcification in the gloves seized his joints, the ceramic material spreading slightly, fusing his hand into a claw around the leather strap. He tried to let go. His fingers wouldn't respond.
He had to use his other hand to pry each finger open, one at a time, forcing the calcified joints to bend. It was loud ΓÇö the creak of ceramic grinding against bone. It was clumsy. It was public.
Bjorn watched. He didn't look away. He didn't offer pity.
"Hands remembering the grip, eh?"
He finished the knot and stood, brushing snow off his knees.
"I knew a guy in the War... held a spear so long they had to break his fingers to get it out of his hand after he died. Said the iron felt more like him than his own skin by the end."
He looked at Kyboh's gloves, at the grey calcification spreading up his forearms.
"Sometimes the weapon doesn't want to let go of you. Sometimes you don't want to let go of it, either."
He climbed back onto the bench.
"We'll get you to that forge. But you need to decide ΓÇö are you fixing the gloves because you want your hands back? Or because you're not ready to become the weapon yet?"
He didn't wait for an answer. He took up the reins.
"Let's move."
What Kyboh didn't mention ΓÇö what he wasn't sure he'd imagined ΓÇö was that when he'd held the strap, the gloves had pulled slightly northward. Like a compass seeking iron. Not punishment. Guidance.
The gloves wanted to go to the forge. They were vibrating in time with something distant ΓÇö a hammer, a heartbeat, a frequency only they could hear.
Kyboh wasn't just broken. He was being summoned.
The Mulch
Late afternoon, first day. The cart rounded a bend in the frozen mountain pass, and the road was blocked.
Refugees. Thirty, maybe more, scattered across the frozen path. They were fleeing from Eastmarch, heading west toward the coast, and they were sick.
The smell hit them before they saw the details. Not the clean rot of a corpse ΓÇö something organic and alive. Wet wood. Fungus. Moss growing where it shouldn't.
Grey, woody patches on their skin. Bark-like growths spreading up arms and across faces. Some had roots ΓÇö thin, black roots ΓÇö growing from their shoulders and necks, curling back toward the southeast like they were being pulled home.
Children were crying. A woman was coughing, each breath wet and labored. A man collapsed into the snow and didn't get up. No one stopped to help him. They just kept moving.
A medic ΓÇö an older Nord woman with a bloodstained apron ΓÇö spotted Davinia's armor and stepped forward, desperation in her eyes.
"Please, milady. We need a healer. My supplies are gone. I don't know what this is. Please."
The cart slowed. Saijah's head was pounding ΓÇö the proximity to the corruption triggering her migraine, the Eldergleam's death-scream echoing through whatever connection these roots shared with the dying tree.
Alfonso leaned forward, studying the refugees with professional interest. Not compassion. Analysis.
"Dagonic," he said quietly. "The rot signature. It's not biological ΓÇö it's metaphysical. The corruption from the Eldergleam. The same thing we saw in Thornheart Grove, but wilder. Uncontrolled." He wrinkled his nose with something like distaste. "Sloppy work."
Varon stepped beside Saijah. His hand found her shoulder ΓÇö steadying, grounding. He spoke quietly, only to her.
"They are already mulch, Vena. The corruption has rooted. They will die whether you help them or not. The only question is whether you waste your strength delaying the inevitable."
He met her eyes.
"Focus on the source. The tree. The cultists poisoning it. These people are symptoms. Symptoms die when you cure the disease."
Davinia looked at the suffering ΓÇö the children, the wounds, the people dying in the snow ΓÇö and felt the knife twist. She knew, with a certainty that tasted like bile, that Danica could have fixed this in seconds. Restoration magic. Cure Disease. Remove the roots with a spell and a touch.
But Davinia had sent her away. Had smacked her hands aside at Korvanjund. Had driven her into the wilderness with nothing but a carved symbol and two thousand gold.
The Crown whispered: These people are structurally irrelevant. A resource drain. Acceptable losses.
"We push through," Davinia said. Her voice was flat. "We can't help them."
Bjorn said nothing. He flicked the reins and guided the cart around the refugees and kept moving. The medic's face crumpled as they passed. Some of the refugees begged. Some cursed. Most just stared with hollow eyes as the cart rolled by, carrying heroes who had chosen not to stop.
Saijah's migraine pulsed behind her eyes. Varon's hand remained on her shoulder until they were out of sight. His grip was steady, warm, and completely certain.
Behind them, the man who had collapsed in the snow did not get up.
The Handler
The cart was grinding through a steep incline, wheels crunching through packed snow. Varon fell into step with Orion, his boots silent on the frozen ground. He had been quiet for most of the journey ΓÇö observing, calculating, filing information away behind those surgically altered features.
"Timeline?"
The single word landed like a stone in still water.
Orion glanced at him. Varon's expression was neutral, professional, but there was an edge beneath it that hadn't been there before. Something fraying.
"When are we going to get this done?" Varon continued, his voice low and precise. "I want to go home. I am not adapted to the cold world of Skyrim and I am here until you finish your contract. The longer this takes, the worse things are for both of us."
He looked at Orion directly.
"Please. Give me a timeline."
Orion didn't answer. Or rather, he answered with something vague and unconvincing ΓÇö words that said nothing and promised less. The kind of deflection that told Varon everything he needed to know about how seriously his associate was taking the obligation.
Varon's jaw tightened. He didn't press further. He didn't need to. The message had been delivered: patience was not unlimited, and the Brotherhood did not forget its contracts.
He dropped back and resumed walking alongside the cart in silence, his hand resting on the pommel of his short sword, his modified Bosmer features set in an expression of controlled frustration.
Orion felt the Ring of the Pale Regent burn cold against his finger. Valerius was always listening. Varon was always watching. And the contract was always waiting.
Three leashes. One neck.
The Ice Queen
Evening, first day. The cart had stopped for the night. Bjorn was tending to Mable. The party was setting up around a fire that struggled against the Pale's wind.
Davinia sat apart from the others, staring into the flames with the thousand-yard gaze of someone looking at something very far away. The Crown's cold radiance made her face look carved from marble in the firelight.
Ylva dropped down onto the log beside her without asking, close enough that their shoulders touched. She held out a wineskin.
"One for you, one for me. Unless you're too much of an Ice Queen to drink with someone who actually lives."
Davinia looked at the wineskin, then at Ylva. The Nord woman was grinning ΓÇö not with menace or mockery, but with the pure, uncomplicated energy of someone who found everything about this situation delightful.
"You've been sitting there all day like a statue," Ylva continued. "Staring at nothing. Frozen from the inside out. You've got all this power. All this cold. But you're not using it. You're just... sitting there. Freezing yourself. Wasting it."
She leaned in slightly.
"I could warm you up. Bet that Crown would crack if you let yourself feel something besides cold. Just saying."
Davinia's glare could have frozen the sun.
"Ooh, THERE it is!" Ylva's grin widened. She leaned back, utterly delighted. "That glare! That glare could freeze the sun. I KNEW there was fire in there somewhere."
Despite everything ΓÇö despite the letter and the refugees and the Crown's whispers and the weight of three competing masters ΓÇö something twitched at the corner of Davinia's mouth. Not a smile. Not quite. But the ghost of one, killed before it could fully form.
"You're impossible," Davinia said.
"I'm fun," Ylva corrected. "There's a difference."
She took a swig from her own wineskin and stretched her legs out toward the fire.
"This is going to be fun."
Across the camp, Bjorn was watching. He sat by the cart, running a curry comb over Mable's flank, his pipe sending thin smoke into the freezing air. Saijah had settled beside him, close enough to share warmth, close enough to feel like belonging.
"She's persistent," Saijah observed, nodding toward Ylva and Davinia.
"Aye." Bjorn's voice was warm but careful. "She's a force of nature, that one. Good to have around. Good for Davinia, maybe. Someone who doesn't want anything from her except... her."
Saijah was quiet for a moment. Then: "You think Varon is good for me?"
Bjorn's hand paused on the curry comb. Just for a second. Then he resumed, his voice as steady as before.
"I think Varon is good at what he does, lass. Very good. And I think you're smart enough to know the difference between someone who cares about you and someone who finds you useful."
He didn't look at her. Didn't push. Just kept grooming the horse, his weathered hands moving with practiced care over Mable's coat.
"I've seen a lot of people in my years on the road," he said. "The ones who tell you what you want to hear right when you're hurting ΓÇö those are the ones you watch closest. Not because they're always wrong. Sometimes they're right. But the timing's too perfect. And a man my age has learned to be suspicious of perfect timing."
He tapped his pipe against the cart wheel, knocking loose ash into the snow.
"You don't need my advice. You're sharp. You'll figure it out. But if you ever want to talk, I'm here. That's all."
He gave Mable a final pat and stood, stretching his back with a series of pops.
"Get some sleep, lass. Long road tomorrow."

PART III: WINTERHOLD
The Homecoming
They crested the final rise on the second day, and Winterhold came into view.
It was worse than they remembered.
The city clung to the cliff like a wounded animal ΓÇö broken, desperate, but still alive. The buildings were patched with mismatched wood and frozen sailcloth. Smoke rose from chimneys, but it was thin, weak. The people here were surviving, not living. Eighty percent of the city had been swallowed by the Great Collapse decades ago. What remained was a desperate slum of fifty people, staring up at the pristine College on its pillar with a mixture of resentment and awe.
But the Wardens had saved this city once. They had stopped the Pale Lady. Without them, Winterhold would be a graveyard.
The guards at the gate spotted the cart. One of them squinted, then his eyes went wide.
"Bjorn! You old trout!"
He turned to the other guard, grinning.
"By Ysmir, it's the Obsidian Lanterns! Open the gate!"
The welcome was genuine. No toll, no identification, no suspicion. Just gratitude.
"We didn't think you'd come back," the guard said, almost breathless. "Not after Kynesgrove. We heard you fought a dragon and lived. Dragon-slayers now, eh?"
He gestured toward the Frozen Hearth.
"Dagny's got your rooms ready. She always keeps them ready, just in case. Said if you ever came back, you drink free for life."
He looked at the party with something that might have been tears forming in the cold air.
"Thank you. For what you did. For the Pale Lady. This place would be dead if not for you."
They didn't stop. Bjorn drove the cart through the gate and past the Frozen Hearth without pulling over, though Davinia saw Dagny in the doorway, axe in hand from splitting firewood, her face breaking into a genuine smile that faded to confusion as the cart rolled past without slowing.
"No time," Bjorn said, answering the question nobody had asked. His voice carried the weight of apology. "Every hour we spend here is an hour Hemming doesn't have."
Varon and Ylva stayed behind. Ylva gave the party a cheerful wave and headed for the Frozen Hearth's bar with the easy confidence of someone who would be perfectly fine on her own. Varon simply stopped walking. He stood at the edge of the slum and watched the cart continue toward the College pillar, his modified features unreadable, before turning to follow Ylva inside.
The cart rolled on, up the frozen road toward the Great Bridge and the shimmer of magic that sealed the College from the dying town below.
The Bridge of Sigils
The bridge was ancient, crumbling, and treacherous ΓÇö a massive stone causeway connecting the slum to the College pillar, older than the Empire. Cracks spiderwebbed across the stones. Ice had formed in the gaps. The wind screamed across the open span, and below, the Sea of Ghosts crashed against rocks hundreds of feet down.
Ahead, a shimmering wall of blue light blocked the far end. It hummed with power, crackling faintly like distant thunder.
Standing at a stone guard booth was an Altmer woman. She was tall, pale, and utterly exhausted. Her robes were pristine, but her hands glowed with latent Destruction magic ΓÇö ready to incinerate anyone who tried to force their way past.
She saw them approaching and raised one hand.
"Halt."
Faralda's voice carried the flat authority of someone who had been standing guard for too long and had no patience left.
"The Arch-Mage has sealed the College. No visitors. No traders. No students. State your business or turn back. I don't have time for tourists."
Alfonso stepped forward first.
"Faralda."
The Altmer's eyes narrowed. Recognition flickered across her exhausted features ΓÇö followed immediately by something more complicated. Distaste, memory, and the specific kind of resignation reserved for former colleagues who had brought shame on the institution.
"Alfonso Duet. I'd heard you were still alive." She didn't make it sound like a compliment. "You were dismissed from this College for a reason. Several reasons, as I recall."
"And yet here I am," Alfonso said. "Circumstances change."
Faralda studied him for a long moment. The ghoul fragments ΓÇö shambling somewhere behind the cart in four separate, slowly reforming pieces ΓÇö were mercifully out of sight.
"The quarantine doesn't apply to disgraced members," she said finally. "You may enter. But if you cause trouble, I will remind you why you were dismissed."
She turned to the others.
"The rest of you. Prove you belong. This is a College, not a mercenary guild."
Kyboh pulled the ancient shield from his pack. The moment the light hit the snowflake crest engraved on its surface, Faralda froze.
She stepped forward, her exhaustion momentarily forgotten.
"Where did you get that?"
Her voice was sharp, urgent.
"That crest... that geometry... that's Pre-Collapse. That's Atmoran."
She reached out as if to touch it, then stopped herself.
"Urag needs to see this. The Arcanaeum needs to catalogue this." She looked at Kyboh directly. "You. You may pass. Go straight to the Arcanaeum and show this to Urag gro-Shub. He'll know what it is."
Orion held out his hand, showing the Ring of the Pale Regent. Faralda leaned closer, studying the enchantment. Her eyes narrowed ΓÇö and something else passed across her face. Something that lingered a fraction too long before she masked it.
"That enchantment... older than the Empire. Vampiric resonance."
She looked up at Orion, and for just a moment, something knowing passed between them. Something that had nothing to do with rings or enchantments and everything to do with recognition.
"The Enchanters will want to see that. You may pass."
She didn't elaborate. But her gaze held his for a beat too long ΓÇö one predator acknowledging another across the barrier of polite fiction.
Saijah stepped forward, and Faralda moved to block her.
"No magic. No scholarship. No entry."
"I'm their Warden," Saijah said calmly. Then her hands moved ΓÇö not in a fighting stance, but in the precise somatic gestures of an Apprentice spell. Light bent around her body, and she vanished.
Invisibility.
Faralda stared at the empty space where Saijah had been standing. Her lips pressed together.
"The invisibility spell," Saijah's voice said from slightly to the left of where she'd disappeared. "Apprentice level. I'm competent."
Faralda's expression suggested she wasn't entirely convinced but was too tired to argue. "Fine. Drop it. You may pass. But that wasn't the Invisibility spell ΓÇö the somatic sequence was wrong."
"Close enough," Saijah said, reappearing.
Faralda let it go. She had bigger problems.
Then Davinia stepped forward.
"Show me what you can do," Faralda said.
Davinia raised her hand, channelling Magicka the way she always had. She intended to cast Firebolt ΓÇö a simple, clean demonstration of Destruction magic.
But the moment the spell began to form, something was wrong.
The heat didn't come. Instead: cold. Biting, absolute cold.
Her hand didn't glow orange. It glowed blue-white.
Geometric fractals of ice manifested in the air before her palm ΓÇö sharp, crystalline, impossibly complex. They spun and locked into place like the tumblers of a lock clicking shut. The somatic gestures her hands performed were not the ones she'd intended. They were different ΓÇö precise, ancient, flowing through her fingers with a fluency she had never learned.
A low tonal hum filled the air. Not the crackling of fire. Not the hiss of flame. A hum, like the resonance of a bell made of glass.
The spell released.
A shard of black ice ΓÇö darker than obsidian, colder than winter ΓÇö shot from her hand and embedded itself in the stone guardrail. The stone shattered. The cold spread outward in a spiderweb of frost, and they heard the faint sound of glass breaking as the ice locked into its final form.
She hadn't cast Firebolt.
She had cast something ancient. Something Atmoran. Something the Crown had taught her without asking permission.
The bridge went silent.
Faralda stared at the shattered stone, at the spreading frost, at Davinia's hands. Then at the Crown on her head.
"What... what was that?"
She stepped closer.
"That wasn't fire. That was ice. But not normal ice. That was Architectural Tonalism. That's Pre-Collapse magic. That's..."
She looked at Davinia's face, then at the Crown.
"You're wearing a relic. An active one. And it's teaching you."
Her expression hardened.
"Urag needs to see you too. And Mirabelle. And probably the Arch-Mage. That artifact is dangerous. If you don't know how to control it..."
She stepped aside.
"You may pass. But you will go to the Arcanaeum and explain to Urag exactly where you got that Crown and what it's been doing to your magic. Do you understand?"
Davinia nodded. Her hands were still cold. The Crown hummed ΓÇö satisfied, proud, proprietary. Ismara's magic had replaced hers, and the demonstration had been flawless.
The fire was gone. The ice had taken its place. And Davinia hadn't chosen any of it.
Faralda lowered the barrier.
"I'm not locking the town out of spite," she said as they passed through. "I'm locking them out because something is happening in the Midden. Something below the College is pulsing."
She looked at each of them.
"We're containing it. If you enter, you enter a quarantine zone. Do not go into the Midden. Do not disturb the wards. And if you hear the pulse..."
She hesitated.
"Ignore it. It will pass."
The shimmering wall of blue light flickered and faded. The way was open.

PART IV: THE CITY ON THE PIN
The Revelation
The gates of the Great Bridge swung inward, and the wind died instantly, cut off by weather-wards they could not see.
Before them lay a sprawling plaza of white stone that hummed with heat. This was not a courtyard. This was not a school.
This was a city built on the head of a pin.
To the left, the Market of Sparks. Stalls floated a few inches off the ground, tended by Mage-Merchants trading Soul Gems like currency. A Frost Atronach lumbered past, carrying heavy crates of books on its back like a common laborer.
Above, three massive towers pierced the sky, connected not by stone but by bridges of hard-light and floating masonry that drifted between them, creating a shifting web of walkways hundreds of feet above the ground. Students and Masters moved between them, stepping confidently onto transparent platforms that flickered and hummed with Magicka.
The air tasted of ozone and old paper. The sky above was locked in a permanent state of auroral twilight ΓÇö green and purple lights dancing across magical shields so powerful they warped the atmosphere itself.
There were no guards here. Only Magic Anomalies ΓÇö crackling, bound elementals ΓÇö leashed to pylons, their energy arcing between containment runes.
This was a place where physics was a suggestion, and magic was the only law.
They had entered the College of Winterhold.
The Pulse
A Breton woman in pristine blue robes intercepted them before they could take five steps onto the plaza. She was flanked by two massive Frost Atronachs, and she looked like she hadn't slept in a week. Her hair was pulled back in a severe bun, and she carried a glowing ledger that wrote itself.
"Faralda signaled you were coming," she said briskly. "Specialists. I am Mirabelle Ervine, Master Wizard and Head of Administration. Welcome to the College of Winterhold."
She gestured sharply, and each of them felt a warm pulse of magic against their chest. Small brass amulets materialized, hanging from invisible chains around their necks.
"Guest tokens. Wear them visibly. The automated defenses will incinerate anyone without one. You are free to use the dormitories, the library, and the market. But ΓÇö"
She looked at each of them seriously.
"The Hall of the Elements is on absolute lockdown. Do not approach the sealed doors. Do not tamper with the wards. And if you hear the pulse..."
She hesitated. The same hesitation as Faralda.
"Ignore it. It will pass."
As if on cue, the ground vibrated. Not an earthquake ΓÇö something rhythmic. A deep, metallic thud that echoed up from below.
THUD... THUD... THUD...
The Anomalies leashed to the pylons flared brighter, straining against their chains. The sound reverberated in their bones.
Everyone felt it. But Saijah felt it like a spike driven through her skull.
The pulse hit her migraine like a hammer. She staggered, one hand going to the cart for support. She felt it in her teeth, in the roots of her connection to the Green.
It felt like the Eldergleam's scream ΓÇö but wrong. Metallic. Artificial. Cold.
It wasn't alive. It wasn't natural. It was something built. Something ancient. Something that should not exist.
And beneath the metallic thrumming, she heard something else: the sound of roots cracking stone. The corruption from Eastmarch had traveled through the earth. It was here. It was digging.
"Are you alright?" Bjorn asked, his hand finding her elbow.
"Fine," Saijah lied. "Just the wind."
Bjorn didn't believe her. But he didn't push. He never pushed.
High above, on a jutting stone balcony projecting from the Hall of the Elements, a figure stood perfectly still. An Altmer in pristine Thalmor robes ΓÇö black and gold, immaculately tailored. He was watching the courtyard. He was watching them.
When Davinia's eyes met his, he gave a slow, deliberate bow. Mocking. Controlled. A predator acknowledging prey.
Ancano.
Mirabelle followed Davinia's gaze upward and her expression tightened. She said nothing about the Thalmor advisor. She didn't need to.
"Your guest quarters are on the third floor of the Hall of Attainment," she said instead. "You can rest there whenever you need. The College is yours to explore."
She turned back to her duties, her Frost Atronach escort falling into step behind her.
The Wardens stood in the plaza of the College of Winterhold ΓÇö a magical metropolis suspended above the sea, humming with power and secrets, quarantined against something pulsing in its depths.
Bjorn parked the cart in the plaza and began checking harnesses, his movements steady, his face calm. He looked up at the towers, at the floating bridges, at the auroral light dancing across the sky, and shook his head slowly.
"Well," he said. "This is something."
The College awaited. And beneath it all, something was pulsing.

ΓÇö End of The Winter Road ΓÇö

